1
00:00:14,348 --> 00:00:16,598
[director] <i>Part of this is</i>
<i>I'm trying to figure out</i>

2
00:00:16,683 --> 00:00:18,193
<i>some of the big picture things.</i>

3
00:00:18,268 --> 00:00:21,358
<i>How aesthetically to tell your story.</i>

4
00:00:21,438 --> 00:00:25,108
<i>And even before that,</i>
<i>kind of what your story is, you know?</i>

5
00:00:26,652 --> 00:00:28,152
<i>Roll, camera.</i>

6
00:00:29,321 --> 00:00:31,491
[Christoph] <i>I've been thinking about</i>

7
00:00:31,573 --> 00:00:34,913
<i>how we would kind of</i>
<i>create the documentary.</i>

8
00:00:36,286 --> 00:00:40,366
<i>And in my general state of anxiety</i>
<i>right now, I came to this question:</i>

9
00:00:40,457 --> 00:00:43,247
<i>Is this about me, or is this by me?</i>

10
00:00:43,335 --> 00:00:45,455
And you don't even see me drawing, right?

11
00:00:46,046 --> 00:00:49,506
[director] We don't. We're just seeing
the top half of your head.

12
00:00:49,591 --> 00:00:51,131
So you can act with your eyes.

13
00:00:52,511 --> 00:00:53,851
[director laughs]

14
00:00:54,721 --> 00:00:57,471
[Cristoph] <i>When I design</i>
<i>the experience for the viewer,</i>

15
00:00:58,058 --> 00:01:00,978
<i>of course I want to come across</i>
<i>as good as I possibly can.</i>

16
00:01:01,061 --> 00:01:03,111
<i>'Cause we're vain and we have to be.</i>

17
00:01:03,605 --> 00:01:04,815
<i>And if it's about me,</i>

18
00:01:04,898 --> 00:01:09,738
<i>it's a little bit, just tug of war</i>
<i>of how much do you make me reveal</i>

19
00:01:09,820 --> 00:01:13,820
<i>and how much do I reveal</i>
<i>of stuff that I might not want to reveal.</i>

20
00:01:14,491 --> 00:01:17,491
<i>But, ultimately, it's not about me.</i>

21
00:01:19,788 --> 00:01:21,038
[director] Be an artist.

22
00:01:22,499 --> 00:01:24,039
[Cristoph whispers] Be an artist.

23
00:01:24,126 --> 00:01:25,706
[drumming]

24
00:01:48,609 --> 00:01:50,689
[woman sings in German]

25
00:02:49,169 --> 00:02:50,879
[clock ticks loudly]

26
00:02:50,962 --> 00:02:53,802
[door opens and closes distantly]

27
00:02:53,882 --> 00:02:57,972
[Christoph] <i>I would say everything</i>
<i>that happens between nine and six</i>

28
00:02:58,053 --> 00:02:59,393
<i>is about work.</i>

29
00:03:05,060 --> 00:03:06,850
<i>I work mostly by myself.</i>

30
00:03:08,688 --> 00:03:11,688
<i>So I sit at my desk and I draw</i>
<i>and I design.</i>

31
00:03:12,776 --> 00:03:13,896
<i>So I'm there,</i>

32
00:03:13,985 --> 00:03:17,605
<i>and it's me and my art supplies</i>
<i>and my computer and my coffee maker,</i>

33
00:03:17,697 --> 00:03:20,117
<i>so it's kind of me, me, me.</i>

34
00:03:24,121 --> 00:03:26,961
<i>I'm such a control freak</i>
<i>that I would always love to sit down</i>

35
00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:30,790
<i>and come up with the perfect formula</i>
<i>for creating art.</i>

36
00:03:31,711 --> 00:03:33,421
<i>But it doesn't work that way.</i>

37
00:03:35,340 --> 00:03:37,430
<i>It's a little bit</i>
<i>of a painful realization,</i>

38
00:03:37,509 --> 00:03:41,679
<i>because, ultimately, it really is,</i>
<i>to a very large degree,</i>

39
00:03:41,763 --> 00:03:42,973
<i>staring at paper.</i>

40
00:03:44,182 --> 00:03:50,022
<i>And I have to trust</i>
<i>for kind of crazy moments to happen.</i>

41
00:03:54,234 --> 00:03:56,244
[piano plays]

42
00:04:06,955 --> 00:04:13,375
<i>I would say that abstraction probably is,</i>
<i>for me, the most important concept of art.</i>

43
00:04:14,796 --> 00:04:17,586
<i>Where you say,</i>
<i>"Oh, I'm just drawing a simple box,</i>

44
00:04:17,674 --> 00:04:20,434
<i>because I love things</i>
<i>that are not precious."</i>

45
00:04:20,886 --> 00:04:24,556
<i>But it's the idea of, like, I start</i>
<i>with a thousand different thoughts</i>

46
00:04:24,639 --> 00:04:27,179
<i>and then I, one by one,</i>
<i>throw them all out,</i>

47
00:04:27,267 --> 00:04:30,347
<i>until, at the end,</i>
<i>I have the one or two or three</i>

48
00:04:30,437 --> 00:04:32,517
<i>that are essential to the whole question.</i>

49
00:04:34,900 --> 00:04:36,860
<i>But the abstraction, for me,</i>

50
00:04:36,943 --> 00:04:42,413
<i>is this idea of getting rid of everything</i>
<i>that's not essential to making a point.</i>

51
00:05:01,426 --> 00:05:05,256
This thing here, it's called
<i>The Good Shape </i>or <i>The Good Form</i>.

52
00:05:05,347 --> 00:05:09,887
So I take this flatiron shape
and I start doing things out of it.

53
00:05:09,976 --> 00:05:11,306
Men, women,

54
00:05:13,730 --> 00:05:18,820
bathroom, strongman, nuclear power plant,

55
00:05:18,902 --> 00:05:20,322
cowboys and Indians,

56
00:05:21,822 --> 00:05:23,702
all sorts of sports.

57
00:05:23,782 --> 00:05:26,582
[director] So what did your teachers
make of you?

58
00:05:26,910 --> 00:05:30,460
<i>I had a very, very difficult teacher,</i>
<i>Heinz Edelmann,</i>

59
00:05:30,539 --> 00:05:32,999
<i>who did </i>Yellow Submarine,
<i>The Beatles' movie,</i>

60
00:05:33,083 --> 00:05:35,593
<i>and did amazing posters and book work.</i>

61
00:05:36,086 --> 00:05:41,676
Fantastic designer, but let's say
he did not teach by encouragement.

62
00:05:41,758 --> 00:05:44,638
The highest compliment that
you could hope for was,

63
00:05:45,011 --> 00:05:47,641
"Oh, we don't really have
a problem with that."

64
00:05:47,722 --> 00:05:49,182
That was like, "Yes!"

65
00:05:51,810 --> 00:05:55,230
<i>When I grew up in South Western Germany,</i>
<i>I was always drawing.</i>

66
00:05:56,731 --> 00:05:59,821
<i>It was all about getting action</i>
<i>and proportion right.</i>

67
00:06:00,318 --> 00:06:02,608
<i>Drawing things very dynamic.</i>

68
00:06:04,614 --> 00:06:06,164
<i>And that was the goal.</i>

69
00:06:06,241 --> 00:06:10,661
<i>To kind of get there, to this, like,</i>
<i>hyperrealist, amazing painting.</i>

70
00:06:10,745 --> 00:06:14,325
<i>And this is kind of the notion</i>
<i>that I went to art school with.</i>

71
00:06:15,625 --> 00:06:18,625
<i>But the teacher I had at art school,</i>
<i>Mr. Edelmann,</i>

72
00:06:18,712 --> 00:06:22,922
<i>he made it pretty clear that he really</i>
<i>disliked this stuff that I was doing.</i>

73
00:06:24,968 --> 00:06:30,098
So I was drawing hundreds of sketches
on just letter-sized paper,

74
00:06:30,181 --> 00:06:32,811
and each week, he would come in
and go through them

75
00:06:32,892 --> 00:06:36,152
and basically say, "Nope, nope,
nope, nope, nope, nope, nope."

76
00:06:36,563 --> 00:06:37,523
"Oh, this one's okay!"

77
00:06:38,690 --> 00:06:40,400
'Cause this is what we did in school.

78
00:06:40,483 --> 00:06:42,903
Take a topic, like a red clown's nose,

79
00:06:42,986 --> 00:06:45,606
and then just squeeze the hell out of it.

80
00:06:45,697 --> 00:06:48,907
Just do every single variation.

81
00:06:49,576 --> 00:06:50,946
[director laughs]

82
00:06:52,287 --> 00:06:57,207
[Cristoph] <i>Eventually, I realized that</i>
<i>it's not about something super simple</i>

83
00:06:57,292 --> 00:06:59,542
<i>like a black square or, like, one line.</i>

84
00:07:00,045 --> 00:07:03,465
But each idea requires
a very specific amount of information.

85
00:07:03,548 --> 00:07:06,638
Sometimes it's a lot: a lot of details,
a lot of realism.

86
00:07:06,718 --> 00:07:10,138
Sometimes it's really just
this one line. The one pixel.

87
00:07:10,221 --> 00:07:14,101
But each idea has one moment
on that scale.

88
00:07:14,184 --> 00:07:18,444
<i>So, lets say you want to illustrate</i>
<i>the idea of a heart as a symbol for love.</i>

89
00:07:18,521 --> 00:07:22,651
When you illustrate it,
as just, like, a red square,

90
00:07:22,734 --> 00:07:25,534
which is the ultimate abstraction
of a heart,

91
00:07:25,612 --> 00:07:28,742
nobody knows what you're talking about,
so it totally falls flat.

92
00:07:28,823 --> 00:07:30,413
When you go all the way realistic

93
00:07:30,492 --> 00:07:35,082
and draw an actual heart made out
of flesh and blood and pumping,

94
00:07:35,163 --> 00:07:36,293
it's just so disgusting

95
00:07:36,373 --> 00:07:39,253
that the last thing anybody
would ever think about is love.

96
00:07:39,334 --> 00:07:41,804
And somewhere between
that abstract red square

97
00:07:41,878 --> 00:07:44,128
and the real, kind of butchered heart,

98
00:07:44,214 --> 00:07:48,394
is the graphic shape that kind of looks
like that, and kind of looks like that,

99
00:07:48,468 --> 00:07:52,758
and it's just right to transport
this idea of a symbol for love.

100
00:07:58,770 --> 00:08:02,400
<i>New Yorker</i> covers are the biggest deal
for an illustrator, I think.

101
00:08:03,984 --> 00:08:05,494
Once you see <i>The New Yorker</i> cover once,

102
00:08:05,568 --> 00:08:08,778
you see the history, you see the artist,

103
00:08:08,863 --> 00:08:12,583
you see, most importantly, I guess,
the cultural impact.

104
00:08:13,994 --> 00:08:16,004
This was my... This was the first one.

105
00:08:16,079 --> 00:08:17,709
[director] What was the date?

106
00:08:17,789 --> 00:08:20,749
July 9, 2001, the day I got married.

107
00:08:20,834 --> 00:08:22,464
Which is especially fantastic.

108
00:08:23,962 --> 00:08:27,262
<i>What I love is that this is</i>
<i>what they put on the magazine.</i>

109
00:08:27,340 --> 00:08:29,510
<i>There's no headline.</i>

110
00:08:29,592 --> 00:08:30,842
<i>There's not even a story.</i>

111
00:08:30,927 --> 00:08:35,267
<i>This was July 4, 2001.</i>
<i>It was about the missile shield.</i>

112
00:08:35,348 --> 00:08:38,558
<i>The Dr. Strangelovian generals</i>
<i>who start World War Three.</i>

113
00:08:39,602 --> 00:08:42,152
There's no story about this idea
inside the magazine.

114
00:08:42,230 --> 00:08:45,610
It's almost like the stage is pulled empty
and this is the image for one week.

115
00:08:48,236 --> 00:08:52,866
The second cover
might actually have been... this one.

116
00:08:52,949 --> 00:08:57,159
And, to a strange degree,
this might even be the most exciting one,

117
00:08:57,245 --> 00:09:00,615
because the first cover of <i>The New Yorker</i>
is the Eustace Tilley,

118
00:09:00,707 --> 00:09:03,167
<i>this New York dandy with a top hat.</i>

119
00:09:04,419 --> 00:09:08,299
<i>And we said,</i>
<i>"Let's try to do an icon of an icon."</i>

120
00:09:09,716 --> 00:09:13,296
<i>Making the butterfly just a blue square,</i>
<i>makes absolutely no sense</i>

121
00:09:13,386 --> 00:09:15,216
<i>unless you know the original.</i>

122
00:09:29,277 --> 00:09:31,277
<i>I've done 22, I think.</i>

123
00:09:35,825 --> 00:09:38,195
<i>The thing is,</i>
<i>I never even thought about 22.</i>

124
00:09:39,287 --> 00:09:41,577
<i>You think that</i>
<i>when you've done two or three,</i>

125
00:09:42,665 --> 00:09:45,995
<i>all of a sudden it becomes, like,</i>
<i>"Oh, it's just another job."</i>

126
00:09:46,419 --> 00:09:52,719
<i>It's not, because it's extremely exciting,</i>
<i>but it never becomes easy.</i>

127
00:09:54,344 --> 00:09:56,604
[clock ticking]

128
00:09:56,679 --> 00:09:59,679
[director] <i>So tell me about</i>
<i>this </i>New Yorker <i>cover you're working on.</i>

129
00:09:59,766 --> 00:10:02,096
[Christoph]
<i>I'm doing this virtual reality cover,</i>

130
00:10:02,185 --> 00:10:04,845
<i>which... It's more like augmented reality.</i>

131
00:10:06,439 --> 00:10:11,989
So the idea is I have this magazine open,
on the front or on the back,

132
00:10:12,070 --> 00:10:15,070
now I approach it
with my phone or with my tablet

133
00:10:15,156 --> 00:10:18,116
and then this whole three-dimensional
animation comes out.

134
00:10:18,201 --> 00:10:20,081
And you're just like, "No way!"

135
00:10:20,161 --> 00:10:25,291
There's a lot of kind of levels
of metaphors and drawing to work.

136
00:10:25,375 --> 00:10:29,045
And 3-D and 2-D and back and forth,
and it's kind of like physical and...

137
00:10:31,297 --> 00:10:32,917
<i>And I also knew I couldn't plan.</i>

138
00:10:33,007 --> 00:10:35,757
<i>I couldn't have one idea</i>
<i>that just solves the entire thing.</i>

139
00:10:35,844 --> 00:10:38,814
<i>I had to start somewhere and then say,</i>
<i>"Okay, is this strong enough</i>

140
00:10:38,888 --> 00:10:41,808
<i>or flexible enough</i>
<i>to just go to the next step?"</i>

141
00:10:41,891 --> 00:10:43,601
[clock ticking]

142
00:10:43,685 --> 00:10:47,305
So the magazine, in theory,
opened like that.

143
00:10:48,606 --> 00:10:50,686
But I don't look at a magazine like that,

144
00:10:50,775 --> 00:10:53,185
I think nobody ever looks
at a magazine like that.

145
00:10:53,278 --> 00:10:57,318
So I thought, when I have a magazine,
I might look at it like that,

146
00:10:57,407 --> 00:11:00,737
so, really seeing it
as the inside-outside world.

147
00:11:00,827 --> 00:11:02,077
And I was thinking,

148
00:11:02,162 --> 00:11:05,962
"What's... What's like a very
New York inside/outside scene?"

149
00:11:10,587 --> 00:11:12,547
<i>I realized that a subway...</i>

150
00:11:13,673 --> 00:11:16,183
<i>I have the windows,</i>
<i>I have people sitting in there</i>

151
00:11:16,259 --> 00:11:18,299
<i>and then the whole subway can be...</i>

152
00:11:19,220 --> 00:11:22,220
<i>Yeah, that's the idea of the magazine</i>

153
00:11:22,307 --> 00:11:25,847
as the plane
that the person walks through.

154
00:11:25,935 --> 00:11:28,515
You can see it from the inside
or from the outside.

155
00:11:40,867 --> 00:11:43,867
It's a New York City cab, off-duty,

156
00:11:45,330 --> 00:11:46,500
which you can see...

157
00:11:49,334 --> 00:11:50,754
It's off-duty here.

158
00:11:51,127 --> 00:11:52,917
This is... Let's make it busy.

159
00:11:53,755 --> 00:11:54,665
This one's busy.

160
00:11:54,756 --> 00:11:58,126
It looks better, though,
all black and yellow.

161
00:11:59,010 --> 00:12:00,390
My favorite colors.

162
00:12:01,679 --> 00:12:03,389
It's the restriction with Lego,

163
00:12:03,473 --> 00:12:05,063
the restriction of...

164
00:12:07,560 --> 00:12:10,730
just very low resolution...

165
00:12:10,813 --> 00:12:13,653
It's almost like
a three-dimensional pixel drawing...

166
00:12:15,234 --> 00:12:16,534
that I enjoy so much.

167
00:12:21,783 --> 00:12:23,993
[director]
Why have you done so much New York work?

168
00:12:24,744 --> 00:12:26,544
Well, it started with my connection.

169
00:12:26,621 --> 00:12:29,791
It was the first city I went to
by myself...

170
00:12:29,874 --> 00:12:33,714
and I think there's only one city
in your life that you go to by yourself...

171
00:12:33,795 --> 00:12:35,045
and you own that.

172
00:12:35,129 --> 00:12:38,049
There was no uncle, there were no parents
that paved the way.

173
00:12:38,132 --> 00:12:39,552
<i>It was like my place.</i>

174
00:12:39,634 --> 00:12:41,644
[simple electronic tune playing]

175
00:12:45,974 --> 00:12:48,274
<i>I moved to New York in '97.</i>

176
00:12:51,354 --> 00:12:53,444
<i>To my surprise, when I went there</i>
<i>and showed my book,</i>

177
00:12:54,148 --> 00:12:58,858
<i>I realized that people understood</i>
<i>99% of my work.</i>

178
00:13:00,530 --> 00:13:03,070
<i>Going to a country</i>
<i>that's a few thousand miles away,</i>

179
00:13:03,157 --> 00:13:06,157
<i>and everybody gets everything</i>
<i>is really amazing.</i>

180
00:13:08,162 --> 00:13:10,422
<i>In a very odd way,</i>
<i>I felt very much at home</i>

181
00:13:10,498 --> 00:13:13,418
<i>just being so immersed in</i>
<i>American culture as a kid.</i>

182
00:13:14,877 --> 00:13:17,667
<i>From music, to art, </i>Magnum P.I.

183
00:13:20,466 --> 00:13:22,926
[electronic music continues playing]

184
00:13:49,495 --> 00:13:50,825
[Christoph] <i>Staten Island Ferry.</i>

185
00:13:50,913 --> 00:13:54,423
If you've been on the Staten Island Ferry,
you know that this is it.

186
00:13:54,500 --> 00:13:58,760
This is the essence
of this kind of first tourist moment.

187
00:14:01,090 --> 00:14:05,680
<i>For me, this style is based on culture,</i>
<i>on shared experiences.</i>

188
00:14:06,637 --> 00:14:11,267
<i>This is more interesting than coming up</i>
<i>with a visionary new way of speaking</i>

189
00:14:11,350 --> 00:14:14,020
<i>that people then have to decipher.</i>

190
00:14:16,397 --> 00:14:17,607
[electronic music ends]

191
00:14:17,690 --> 00:14:19,860
[street hubbub]

192
00:14:27,617 --> 00:14:30,997
[Christoph] <i>There's this one Starbucks,</i>
<i>and I love sitting in that window,</i>

193
00:14:31,079 --> 00:14:33,209
<i>and that's been a place</i>
<i>I've been sitting at</i>

194
00:14:33,289 --> 00:14:35,629
<i>from my very first time coming</i>
<i>to New York.</i>

195
00:14:35,708 --> 00:14:39,128
<i>I always felt like, "That's where I want</i>
<i>to sit and kind of look out."</i>

196
00:14:39,212 --> 00:14:42,422
<i>And I've, a couple of times,</i>
<i>tried to work from there,</i>

197
00:14:42,507 --> 00:14:45,507
<i>because that's how I see myself, you know,</i>

198
00:14:45,593 --> 00:14:48,013
<i>like the artist</i>
<i>being in touch with the city...</i>

199
00:14:48,805 --> 00:14:51,765
<i>And then we have</i>
<i>this kind of emotional exchange,</i>

200
00:14:51,849 --> 00:14:52,979
<i>people walking by...</i>

201
00:14:53,059 --> 00:14:54,439
[street hubbub]

202
00:14:54,519 --> 00:14:55,399
[silence]

203
00:14:55,478 --> 00:14:56,938
<i>It doesn't work at all.</i>

204
00:14:57,897 --> 00:15:00,687
<i>The impact on the work is zero.</i>

205
00:15:00,775 --> 00:15:04,235
<i>It's even actually confusing,</i>
<i>and I can't really focus when I sit there.</i>

206
00:15:05,738 --> 00:15:07,448
<i>This is the moment where I realized</i>

207
00:15:07,532 --> 00:15:13,162
<i>that kind of, like, my real life</i>
<i>and my work life, they don't really mix.</i>

208
00:15:14,914 --> 00:15:16,254
[director] <i>I see what you're saying.</i>

209
00:15:17,083 --> 00:15:21,803
<i>I'm just trying to kind of solve it</i>
<i>from a visual storytelling point of view.</i>

210
00:15:22,255 --> 00:15:25,045
<i>I mean, I guess, the way</i>
<i>I see some of these things,</i>

211
00:15:25,133 --> 00:15:29,053
<i>it's almost like these very quick montages</i>
<i>of very close shots,</i>

212
00:15:29,137 --> 00:15:30,967
<i>you know, done very quickly.</i>

213
00:15:31,055 --> 00:15:32,595
<i>Just... </i>[makes sweeping sound]

214
00:15:32,682 --> 00:15:35,602
<i>Getting through the day,</i>
<i>its ritual, like brushing your teeth.</i>

215
00:15:36,185 --> 00:15:38,145
[Christoph] <i>I mean, again we can try...</i>

216
00:15:38,688 --> 00:15:42,018
<i>You know, like, the idea of a camera</i>
<i>in our bathroom...</i>

217
00:15:42,608 --> 00:15:44,358
<i>makes me feel extremely uncomfortable.</i>

218
00:15:45,695 --> 00:15:47,655
[director laughing]
<i>Okay, well I don't want that.</i>

219
00:15:47,738 --> 00:15:50,778
[Christoph] <i>And so we can do it,</i>
<i>but it would be more like a painful thing</i>

220
00:15:50,867 --> 00:15:55,197
<i>and I could not possibly imagine</i>
<i>how I would ever want to see that myself.</i>

221
00:15:55,288 --> 00:15:57,288
[ominous music playing]

222
00:15:57,373 --> 00:15:59,833
<i>I'd much rather draw it than show it.</i>

223
00:16:00,501 --> 00:16:02,751
[ticking clock]

224
00:16:05,381 --> 00:16:08,091
<i>When I started working,</i>
<i>I worked mostly under deadline.</i>

225
00:16:10,928 --> 00:16:13,468
<i>For the first ten years,</i>

226
00:16:14,307 --> 00:16:17,977
if I would have to separate my business,

227
00:16:18,060 --> 00:16:24,570
it was 30% "We need Christoph
to make a nice drawing on this and that"

228
00:16:24,650 --> 00:16:28,530
and 70% of, like,
"Oh, no, something went terribly wrong.

229
00:16:28,613 --> 00:16:31,453
We have another 12 hours,
let's call that guy,

230
00:16:31,532 --> 00:16:34,372
he will make a somewhat
unembarrassing solution

231
00:16:34,452 --> 00:16:37,252
that will save our butts for deadline."

232
00:16:37,788 --> 00:16:40,538
<i>And I love that.</i>
<i>I love this kind of tension,</i>

233
00:16:40,625 --> 00:16:41,785
<i>especially in editorial,</i>

234
00:16:41,876 --> 00:16:45,376
<i>but a lot of the calls I got</i>
<i>were out of desperation.</i>

235
00:16:45,463 --> 00:16:46,423
[clock ticking]

236
00:16:49,592 --> 00:16:52,352
[strings play to a climax]

237
00:17:04,398 --> 00:17:08,398
<i>So I think Chuck Close said,</i>
<i>"Inspiration is for amateurs.</i>

238
00:17:08,903 --> 00:17:12,033
<i>Us professionals,</i>
<i>we just go to work in the morning."</i>

239
00:17:20,039 --> 00:17:22,669
<i>The one thing</i>
<i>I really love about that quote</i>

240
00:17:22,750 --> 00:17:25,000
<i>is it relieves you of a lot of pressure.</i>

241
00:17:25,753 --> 00:17:29,883
<i>It's not about waiting for hours</i>
<i>for this moment where inspiration strikes.</i>

242
00:17:31,050 --> 00:17:33,800
<i>It's just about showing up</i>
<i>and getting started,</i>

243
00:17:33,886 --> 00:17:37,136
<i>and then something amazing happens</i>
<i>or it doesn't happen.</i>

244
00:17:37,223 --> 00:17:41,023
<i>All that matters is you enable</i>
<i>the chance for something to happen.</i>

245
00:17:41,102 --> 00:17:42,732
For that you have to sit at your desk

246
00:17:42,812 --> 00:17:46,772
and you have to draw and do
and make decisions and hope for the best.

247
00:17:46,857 --> 00:17:48,357
[calming music playing]

248
00:17:55,700 --> 00:17:59,200
[Christoph] <i>It's so scary when you have</i>
<i>half an hour to do something.</i>

249
00:17:59,954 --> 00:18:01,664
<i>That of course, creating a process</i>

250
00:18:01,747 --> 00:18:04,957
<i>that allows you to do</i>
<i>unembarrassing stuff on command</i>

251
00:18:05,042 --> 00:18:06,712
<i>is the only way you can survive.</i>

252
00:18:07,503 --> 00:18:09,883
<i>If you create an armor</i>
<i>of craft around you.</i>

253
00:18:14,218 --> 00:18:18,098
<i>The one thing that's dangerous</i>
<i>about focusing on craft</i>

254
00:18:18,180 --> 00:18:19,680
<i>and working very hard</i>

255
00:18:19,765 --> 00:18:24,345
<i>is that it can keep you from asking</i>
<i>the really relevant questions.</i>

256
00:18:24,437 --> 00:18:26,187
<i>I'm trying to get good at something,</i>

257
00:18:26,272 --> 00:18:29,732
<i>but is that thing that I'm trying to</i>
<i>get good at the real thing?</i>

258
00:18:31,819 --> 00:18:36,119
It's the subway track
with the knobs on the side of the tracks.

259
00:18:37,658 --> 00:18:38,578
Put...

260
00:18:40,828 --> 00:18:42,198
someone standing there.

261
00:18:44,332 --> 00:18:48,092
So when you stand there
in the middle of the night,

262
00:18:48,169 --> 00:18:49,839
'cause you missed the last G train

263
00:18:50,546 --> 00:18:52,256
and you just look at the critters,

264
00:18:53,382 --> 00:18:55,382
your friends and your enemies at once.

265
00:18:58,179 --> 00:19:00,139
The yellow is the perfect New York color.

266
00:19:00,222 --> 00:19:03,142
It's the taxicabs,
it's the side of the subways....

267
00:19:06,020 --> 00:19:08,150
The contrast is just so perfect.

268
00:19:08,814 --> 00:19:10,524
[upbeat piano music]

269
00:19:20,951 --> 00:19:22,621
<i>I met my wonderful wife,</i>

270
00:19:22,703 --> 00:19:24,663
<i>we got married and had kids.</i>

271
00:19:26,457 --> 00:19:30,917
We have this routine of, like, waving
at each other when she leaves and comes.

272
00:19:34,423 --> 00:19:35,593
[in German] Have fun.

273
00:19:36,175 --> 00:19:38,675
We're all waiting for you
to leave the frame!

274
00:19:39,428 --> 00:19:41,098
[laughs] It's totally okay.

275
00:19:42,723 --> 00:19:44,273
See you in a bit.

276
00:19:46,477 --> 00:19:50,977
[in English] I guess it started
with me and my wife.

277
00:19:51,565 --> 00:19:56,525
And then we have one kid,
and then it's really more like that.

278
00:19:57,571 --> 00:19:58,951
Then you have a second child.

279
00:19:59,031 --> 00:20:00,741
You think they're like the first one

280
00:20:00,825 --> 00:20:03,405
because you're doing the same thing
you did with the first one,

281
00:20:03,494 --> 00:20:05,414
but the second one
turns out totally different.

282
00:20:05,496 --> 00:20:07,956
But then the third one is more like that.

283
00:20:29,145 --> 00:20:30,305
<i>I did a book</i>

284
00:20:30,396 --> 00:20:33,066
<i>based on the experience</i>
<i>of riding the subway with the kids</i>

285
00:20:33,149 --> 00:20:36,569
and how they just
totally absorbed this idea.

286
00:20:36,652 --> 00:20:39,282
And I think what they liked
about the subway,

287
00:20:39,363 --> 00:20:40,703
what I like about the subway is,

288
00:20:40,781 --> 00:20:43,451
in a strange way,
you're in this huge city,

289
00:20:43,534 --> 00:20:45,544
but it's the one thing
where you're in control.

290
00:21:04,764 --> 00:21:06,274
Sometimes we're like that.

291
00:21:10,519 --> 00:21:11,849
Sometimes like this.

292
00:21:14,523 --> 00:21:17,233
I guess we hope
to be like that more often.

293
00:21:18,736 --> 00:21:22,866
That seems like a realistic rendering
of family life.

294
00:21:30,581 --> 00:21:33,501
I'm trying to come up
with something for <i>The New Yorker.</i>

295
00:21:35,419 --> 00:21:37,509
I'm doing this virtual reality cover,

296
00:21:38,380 --> 00:21:40,800
and basically this is
something I've never done.

297
00:21:42,968 --> 00:21:47,058
<i>In this case, not only do you work 360,</i>
<i>but you work 360 in all directions,</i>

298
00:21:47,139 --> 00:21:49,559
<i>so you can look at it</i>
<i>from all different angles.</i>

299
00:21:57,608 --> 00:22:01,488
<i>For anything decent I've ever done,</i>

300
00:22:01,570 --> 00:22:05,410
<i>I distinctly remember</i>
<i>being in a tense, grumpy mood.</i>

301
00:22:09,620 --> 00:22:13,710
<i>Worse than that, I get suspicious</i>
<i>when having too good of a time working,</i>

302
00:22:13,791 --> 00:22:16,961
<i>since I know that this doesn't bode well</i>
<i>for the outcome.</i>

303
00:22:25,052 --> 00:22:27,762
[clock ticking]

304
00:22:27,846 --> 00:22:30,426
<i>When you draw in two dimensions,</i>
<i>you can cheat.</i>

305
00:22:30,516 --> 00:22:33,136
<i>You can just hide</i>
<i>anything you don't like behind a wall.</i>

306
00:22:33,769 --> 00:22:36,149
<i>And in this case,</i>
<i>you can look behind the wall</i>

307
00:22:36,230 --> 00:22:38,610
<i>and you can see all the mess</i>
<i>that's behind it.</i>

308
00:22:38,691 --> 00:22:40,991
<i>It's like an endless compromise.</i>

309
00:22:42,778 --> 00:22:47,028
<i>The elements are not this kind of, like,</i>
<i>highly-rendered 3-D world,</i>

310
00:22:47,116 --> 00:22:49,536
<i>which I really detest visually.</i>

311
00:22:50,536 --> 00:22:52,406
<i>You know, where everything has highlights</i>

312
00:22:52,496 --> 00:22:54,996
<i>and everything feels</i>
<i>like this smelly plastic.</i>

313
00:22:55,624 --> 00:22:56,754
<i>I want an ink drawing.</i>

314
00:22:56,834 --> 00:23:01,384
<i>I want, like, a flat ink drawing</i>
<i>that you can walk into</i>

315
00:23:01,463 --> 00:23:03,093
<i>and that kind of surrounds you.</i>

316
00:23:05,467 --> 00:23:07,387
There's too many lines in that side.

317
00:23:08,387 --> 00:23:11,557
Just throw in something
that you think you would regret,

318
00:23:11,640 --> 00:23:13,890
and that's usually
the most interesting part.

319
00:23:16,729 --> 00:23:19,399
When all fails,
just put in some water towers.

320
00:23:20,232 --> 00:23:21,982
It's always a great trick.

321
00:23:23,694 --> 00:23:26,494
And this is so wrong with that dry brush.

322
00:23:26,572 --> 00:23:29,242
I wish I could rip out
the rest of the painting

323
00:23:29,325 --> 00:23:30,445
and do more of that.

324
00:23:33,621 --> 00:23:36,251
Obviously I'm playing around
for the camera now.

325
00:23:36,707 --> 00:23:37,787
Dun, dun, dun...

326
00:23:40,252 --> 00:23:42,712
Okay, next scene.

327
00:23:45,841 --> 00:23:48,301
<i>I'm convinced</i>
<i>you always have to change direction</i>

328
00:23:48,385 --> 00:23:49,595
<i>while things are good.</i>

329
00:23:50,929 --> 00:23:53,849
<i>I was in my mid-30s, was extremely busy.</i>

330
00:23:55,476 --> 00:23:58,346
<i>I felt fulfilled, but exhausted.</i>

331
00:24:00,981 --> 00:24:03,651
<i>And I still think New York</i>
<i>is the best place to work,</i>

332
00:24:05,694 --> 00:24:09,744
<i>but I feel like it's not a good place</i>
<i>to refill your kind of creative tank.</i>

333
00:24:13,535 --> 00:24:16,155
<i>And I find it harder to reinvent.</i>

334
00:24:20,167 --> 00:24:24,207
<i>I sensed that the only way to grow</i>
<i>required that I loosen up.</i>

335
00:24:27,257 --> 00:24:29,677
<i>And it was in the mid-2000s,</i>

336
00:24:30,886 --> 00:24:35,806
<i>my wife and I agreed that the only place</i>
<i>that we could imagine to move to</i>

337
00:24:35,891 --> 00:24:36,931
<i>would be Berlin.</i>

338
00:24:37,017 --> 00:24:39,137
[jazz music playing]

339
00:24:39,812 --> 00:24:41,562
[woman sings German lyrics]

340
00:25:33,323 --> 00:25:36,083
[Cristoph] <i>There's all these</i>
<i>kind of crazy galleries</i>

341
00:25:36,160 --> 00:25:39,870
<i>that do stuff that makes absolutely</i>
<i>no sense whatsoever economically</i>

342
00:25:39,955 --> 00:25:42,115
<i>and it's just totally a different mindset.</i>

343
00:25:44,877 --> 00:25:48,627
<i>Berlin makes it easy not to worry so much</i>
<i>about the feasibility of an idea.</i>

344
00:25:49,173 --> 00:25:52,973
<i>So my kind of, like, most intense phase,</i>
<i>in terms of my work,</i>

345
00:25:53,051 --> 00:25:55,261
<i>actually happened when I moved to Berlin.</i>

346
00:25:56,013 --> 00:25:57,813
[German song continues]

347
00:26:16,408 --> 00:26:18,738
[director] <i>In a perfect world,</i>
<i>in this documentary,</i>

348
00:26:18,827 --> 00:26:20,907
<i>and this will probably make you queasy,</i>

349
00:26:20,996 --> 00:26:25,746
<i>there would be a moment where</i>
<i>there's a sense of unadulterated reality.</i>

350
00:26:25,834 --> 00:26:27,044
<i>Just a glimpse.</i>

351
00:26:28,086 --> 00:26:29,506
[Christoph] <i>I...</i>

352
00:26:30,798 --> 00:26:34,798
<i>It would feel so completely out of place.</i>

353
00:26:34,885 --> 00:26:38,965
<i>Like, it would be the farthest thing</i>
<i>from me ever showing anybody</i>

354
00:26:39,056 --> 00:26:40,386
<i>how I brush my teeth.</i>

355
00:26:41,058 --> 00:26:43,808
<i>When you show the real thing, you kill it.</i>

356
00:26:44,311 --> 00:26:47,731
You make it impossible to then look
at these things in the abstract.

357
00:26:47,815 --> 00:26:53,355
It's like in... I think in Charlie Brown,
you never see the grown-ups,

358
00:26:53,445 --> 00:26:55,855
-you only hear these muffled voices,
-[muffled voice]

359
00:26:55,948 --> 00:26:57,698
and that's perfect, that's amazing!

360
00:26:57,783 --> 00:27:00,413
The one moment you zoom out
and show these grownups,

361
00:27:00,494 --> 00:27:03,754
they could be designed perfectly,
they could be written perfectly,

362
00:27:03,831 --> 00:27:05,871
but everything else
would be crashing down.

363
00:27:05,958 --> 00:27:09,628
So, in a way, I feel like
we already zoomed out and showed,

364
00:27:09,711 --> 00:27:11,631
even though I don't know
if I'm a grown-up,

365
00:27:11,713 --> 00:27:15,013
but that's already far too big
of a zoom out.

366
00:27:15,092 --> 00:27:17,432
And if you go even further there...

367
00:27:17,928 --> 00:27:23,348
[director] So much of your daily routine
and life inspires your work.

368
00:27:23,433 --> 00:27:26,103
It just seems
like we should be able to see it.

369
00:27:29,189 --> 00:27:31,019
Well, yeah. I guess. Yeah.

370
00:27:32,484 --> 00:27:33,444
[stammers]

371
00:27:33,569 --> 00:27:36,449
<i>Okay, honestly nobody wants authenticity.</i>

372
00:27:36,530 --> 00:27:39,030
Authenticity is like changing
your kid's diapers.

373
00:27:39,116 --> 00:27:43,196
It's a cute idea in the abstract,
but the real deal is just...

374
00:27:44,413 --> 00:27:46,713
<i>All I care about</i>
<i>is what's happening on the page,</i>

375
00:27:46,790 --> 00:27:50,670
<i>because I want people</i>
<i>to really think about themselves.</i>

376
00:27:52,921 --> 00:27:55,261
<i>What went into creating the art?</i>

377
00:27:55,340 --> 00:27:58,550
[director] But people want to see you
in your real life.

378
00:27:58,635 --> 00:28:01,675
We can't just film you
at your desk the whole documentary.

379
00:28:01,763 --> 00:28:03,433
[electronic music playing]

380
00:28:10,647 --> 00:28:13,107
[Christoph] <i>Anything that's happening</i>
<i>between nine and six</i>

381
00:28:13,192 --> 00:28:14,572
<i>is kind of the essence.</i>

382
00:28:16,737 --> 00:28:19,317
<i>But some stuff has to happen</i>
<i>outside the studio.</i>

383
00:28:20,324 --> 00:28:22,164
<i>Like going to a museum.</i>

384
00:28:27,539 --> 00:28:31,959
<i>The gateway drug is not creating art,</i>
<i>but experiencing art.</i>

385
00:28:37,174 --> 00:28:38,724
[electronic music continues]

386
00:28:47,601 --> 00:28:49,731
[Christoph]
<i>Having the whole world explained,</i>

387
00:28:49,811 --> 00:28:52,191
<i>or even better, turned upside down,</i>

388
00:28:52,272 --> 00:28:56,442
<i>just by looking at</i>
<i>a few strokes of oil paint on canvas.</i>

389
00:29:00,322 --> 00:29:02,372
<i>That's the greatest thrill I know.</i>

390
00:29:09,873 --> 00:29:12,043
<i>If experiencing art is so amazing,</i>

391
00:29:12,125 --> 00:29:14,625
<i>how great must it be</i>
<i>to actually make this stuff?</i>

392
00:29:16,213 --> 00:29:18,383
<i>And that's how they lure you</i>
<i>into art school.</i>

393
00:29:19,716 --> 00:29:21,466
[electronic music continues]

394
00:29:34,815 --> 00:29:37,815
[Christoph]<i> Everything I do</i>
<i>is kind of creating information,</i>

395
00:29:37,901 --> 00:29:42,821
<i>creating usually images that do something</i>
<i>with what the viewer already knows.</i>

396
00:29:42,906 --> 00:29:47,906
<i>Really the idea of, like, their experience</i>
<i>and my experience coming together</i>

397
00:29:47,995 --> 00:29:50,245
<i>and the images are the trigger.</i>

398
00:29:53,834 --> 00:29:59,174
<i>But the big, big problem with routine</i>
<i>is everything starts to look the same.</i>

399
00:29:59,965 --> 00:30:04,965
<i>So I'm constantly trying to reinvent</i>
<i>how I approach image making,</i>

400
00:30:05,053 --> 00:30:06,893
<i>how I approach storytelling,</i>

401
00:30:06,972 --> 00:30:10,182
<i>because the audience changes all the time,</i>
<i>I change all the time.</i>

402
00:30:10,267 --> 00:30:11,847
[chime music playing]

403
00:30:17,607 --> 00:30:20,317
[Christoph]<i> When I was 12,</i>
<i>I taught myself to juggle.</i>

404
00:30:21,653 --> 00:30:24,573
<i>At any given moment,</i>
<i>there's one ball in the air.</i>

405
00:30:24,656 --> 00:30:28,286
<i>And this is something that I hate so much,</i>
<i>this idea of no control.</i>

406
00:30:29,786 --> 00:30:33,706
<i>But this approach of not planning</i>
<i>opens a new door.</i>

407
00:30:36,501 --> 00:30:41,881
<i>It's really, really hard,</i>
<i>but it just leads to these magic moments.</i>

408
00:31:02,694 --> 00:31:05,454
<i>I started an Instagram project</i>
<i>called </i>Sunday Sketches.

409
00:31:06,698 --> 00:31:08,408
<i>In terms of the response I've got,</i>

410
00:31:08,492 --> 00:31:11,332
<i>they've been some of the better stuff</i>
<i>I've been doing,</i>

411
00:31:11,411 --> 00:31:14,831
<i>but on the other hand, they're</i>
<i>the most useless things I've ever done.</i>

412
00:31:18,877 --> 00:31:21,377
<i>There's almost zero control there.</i>

413
00:31:23,632 --> 00:31:25,682
<i>For my professional work, I need control</i>

414
00:31:25,759 --> 00:31:29,049
<i>because I need to be able to tweak,</i>
<i>to adjust, to plan.</i>

415
00:31:34,184 --> 00:31:36,654
<i>But these </i>Sunday Sketches
<i>are un-plannable.</i>

416
00:31:38,230 --> 00:31:42,400
<i>All the good ones just happen</i>
<i>by me just staring at something.</i>

417
00:31:43,985 --> 00:31:46,405
<i>Like moving around the light,</i>
<i>and all of a sudden,</i>

418
00:31:46,488 --> 00:31:50,528
<i>there's a highlight or a shadow and then,</i>
<i>"Oh, now there's something happening."</i>

419
00:31:51,785 --> 00:31:53,195
<i>You can't sketch that.</i>

420
00:32:03,630 --> 00:32:04,670
<i>I never was a reader</i>

421
00:32:04,756 --> 00:32:06,506
<i>because I never want</i>
<i>to escape from anything,</i>

422
00:32:06,591 --> 00:32:08,841
<i>I want my real life to be interesting.</i>

423
00:32:10,095 --> 00:32:11,805
<i>But then I read a book,</i>

424
00:32:11,888 --> 00:32:14,978
The Invention of Slowness,
<i>I think is the title.</i>

425
00:32:17,853 --> 00:32:21,823
<i>It's about a guy who is</i>
<i>so incredibly slow in his perception</i>

426
00:32:21,898 --> 00:32:25,188
<i>that he can...</i>
<i>He actually sees shadows moving.</i>

427
00:32:28,780 --> 00:32:30,070
<i>It's a good fiction book,</i>

428
00:32:30,157 --> 00:32:32,947
<i>but the amazing thing</i>
<i>that I remember from reading that book</i>

429
00:32:33,034 --> 00:32:35,294
<i>is, whenever I looked up from that book,</i>

430
00:32:38,790 --> 00:32:42,750
<i>I felt I had this view from the book</i>
<i>in my real world.</i>

431
00:32:42,836 --> 00:32:44,546
[calming music playing]

432
00:32:53,889 --> 00:32:56,429
<i>This book made my life more interesting.</i>

433
00:33:02,105 --> 00:33:03,395
<i>This is also in art,</i>

434
00:33:03,482 --> 00:33:06,822
<i>something where you're not creating</i>
<i>an artificial world.</i>

435
00:33:09,070 --> 00:33:12,120
<i>You're taking the things you know,</i>

436
00:33:12,991 --> 00:33:15,791
<i>and then you break them down</i>
<i>into little elements.</i>

437
00:33:17,996 --> 00:33:19,456
<i>And I rearrange them,</i>

438
00:33:21,750 --> 00:33:23,590
<i>and all of a sudden make a statement.</i>

439
00:33:23,668 --> 00:33:25,458
[calming music continues]

440
00:33:25,545 --> 00:33:28,665
[Christoph]<i> Not with a monster</i>
<i>or a dragon,</i>

441
00:33:29,341 --> 00:33:30,341
<i>but with a pencil.</i>

442
00:33:40,435 --> 00:33:42,345
<i>I came from, you know, print media.</i>

443
00:33:43,188 --> 00:33:45,568
<i>You just felt like it's always</i>
<i>going to be there,</i>

444
00:33:45,649 --> 00:33:48,239
<i>people always need images</i>
<i>and they always need to be drawn,</i>

445
00:33:48,318 --> 00:33:50,448
<i>and if you've figured it out, you're set.</i>

446
00:33:51,947 --> 00:33:54,027
<i>And all of a sudden, it wasn't anymore.</i>

447
00:33:54,783 --> 00:33:58,583
<i>It was about web long form pieces,</i>
<i>it was about animation.</i>

448
00:34:00,038 --> 00:34:03,878
<i>Of course, it's our job to see</i>
<i>if there's some relevant way</i>

449
00:34:03,959 --> 00:34:06,209
<i>that I can contribute to this new angle.</i>

450
00:34:08,046 --> 00:34:11,466
So this is all of us, all the time.

451
00:34:14,928 --> 00:34:17,138
So this is an app I did
over the last four years,

452
00:34:17,222 --> 00:34:20,022
and I wanted
to do something interactive...

453
00:34:20,684 --> 00:34:21,774
But the big question is

454
00:34:21,851 --> 00:34:27,151
the moment I give too much decision-making
to the viewer over what can happen...

455
00:34:28,191 --> 00:34:30,071
Often, the viewer
might have different ideas,

456
00:34:30,151 --> 00:34:31,401
and you want to be surprised.

457
00:34:31,486 --> 00:34:33,026
That's the whole point of books.

458
00:34:33,113 --> 00:34:36,373
You want some surprise.
You want something unexpected to happen.

459
00:34:43,999 --> 00:34:50,629
But here, in my literary section,
I have all these literature references,

460
00:34:50,714 --> 00:34:52,974
like Don Quixote and Kafka,

461
00:34:55,385 --> 00:34:56,505
Moby Dick,

462
00:34:57,596 --> 00:34:58,966
a little Jane Austen,

463
00:34:59,431 --> 00:35:00,271
and Homer,

464
00:35:00,348 --> 00:35:03,478
and hopefully kids enjoy that scene
as much as grown-ups.

465
00:35:11,026 --> 00:35:11,856
<i>Some people love it,</i>

466
00:35:14,446 --> 00:35:16,026
and probably some people don't.

467
00:35:16,990 --> 00:35:18,200
Some people love it,

468
00:35:19,534 --> 00:35:20,874
some people don't.

469
00:35:20,952 --> 00:35:22,042
That's life.

470
00:35:32,881 --> 00:35:33,881
[swoosh]

471
00:35:34,174 --> 00:35:36,384
[clock ticking]

472
00:35:36,468 --> 00:35:41,888
[director] <i>I'm wondering, it almost seems</i>
<i>like, you know, the creator of your pieces</i>

473
00:35:41,973 --> 00:35:44,023
<i>and you, as editor of your pieces,</i>

474
00:35:44,100 --> 00:35:46,690
<i>are two different people.</i>

475
00:35:46,770 --> 00:35:47,770
[Christoph] <i>Yes!</i>

476
00:35:51,941 --> 00:35:55,321
<i>I need to be in control</i>
<i>and I need to have a very clear sense</i>

477
00:35:55,403 --> 00:35:58,493
<i>of where I'm going and why</i>
<i>something's working and not working.</i>

478
00:36:01,117 --> 00:36:05,957
<i>On the other hand, I've also realized that</i>
<i>being more free-spirited is necessary.</i>

479
00:36:11,086 --> 00:36:14,796
<i>I've found that I need to develop</i>
<i>these two personas separately.</i>

480
00:36:15,465 --> 00:36:20,675
<i>Be a much more ruthless editor</i>
<i>and be a much more careless artist.</i>

481
00:36:28,103 --> 00:36:33,233
<i>This I find physically exhausting,</i>
<i>but there's good stuff happening there.</i>

482
00:36:48,665 --> 00:36:53,455
<i>I take very specific time off</i>
<i>for this kind of, like, free creation.</i>

483
00:36:53,545 --> 00:36:55,625
[clock ticking]

484
00:36:55,714 --> 00:36:58,844
<i>Because I know it's basically impossible</i>
<i>to do under deadline.</i>

485
00:37:02,303 --> 00:37:04,853
<i>Literally, just sitting</i>
<i>in front of a piece of paper</i>

486
00:37:04,931 --> 00:37:08,271
<i>and just doing stuff and being fearless.</i>

487
00:37:11,062 --> 00:37:15,232
<i>There's something there that I need to,</i>
<i>kind of, go back and investigate further.</i>

488
00:37:15,734 --> 00:37:16,994
[clock continues ticking]

489
00:37:20,280 --> 00:37:23,990
[Christoph] <i>Creatively,</i>
<i>I'm extremely dependent on these sparks.</i>

490
00:37:26,953 --> 00:37:31,003
<i>And it only works with loosening up,</i>
<i>without an assignment, without deadline,</i>

491
00:37:31,082 --> 00:37:32,882
<i>with just kind of creating</i>

492
00:37:32,959 --> 00:37:36,549
<i>and not worrying so much</i>
<i>about where the whole thing goes.</i>

493
00:37:39,758 --> 00:37:42,338
<i>But I think it has never happened to me</i>

494
00:37:42,427 --> 00:37:45,217
<i>that I tried something new</i>
<i>on a big deadline.</i>

495
00:37:46,473 --> 00:37:49,183
[director] <i>And what's your deadline</i>
<i>for </i>The New Yorker<i>?</i>

496
00:37:49,267 --> 00:37:50,347
[Christoph] <i>Two weeks.</i>

497
00:37:50,435 --> 00:37:54,265
<i>It's going to be insanity.</i>
<i>Totally stressed out.</i> [laughs]

498
00:37:58,693 --> 00:38:00,703
<i>I've seen a lot of VR stuff,</i>

499
00:38:00,779 --> 00:38:03,659
<i>and it's always, like,</i>
<i>"Oh, wow! This is so interesting,"</i>

500
00:38:04,616 --> 00:38:08,406
<i>and then, 25 seconds later,</i>
<i>I completely lose interest</i>

501
00:38:08,495 --> 00:38:10,785
<i>and this is the great challenge right now.</i>

502
00:38:14,459 --> 00:38:18,509
<i>This is not, like, a coy thing to say,</i>
<i>"Oh, I don't believe I'm talented."</i>

503
00:38:18,588 --> 00:38:22,968
<i>This is real,</i>
<i>like, being absolutely painfully aware</i>

504
00:38:23,051 --> 00:38:26,681
<i>of how you're not good enough</i>
<i>to do something on command.</i>

505
00:38:26,763 --> 00:38:28,223
[chime music playing]

506
00:38:35,438 --> 00:38:38,108
[Christoph] <i>Your general notion</i>
<i>is that doing something nice</i>

507
00:38:38,191 --> 00:38:39,821
<i>makes you more confident.</i>

508
00:38:40,568 --> 00:38:43,238
<i>With ideas,</i>
<i>I often find it's the opposite.</i>

509
00:38:44,113 --> 00:38:47,583
<i>With every good idea you have,</i>
<i>it actually becomes more difficult,</i>

510
00:38:47,659 --> 00:38:49,909
<i>because it's so hard to then repeat.</i>

511
00:38:49,994 --> 00:38:51,374
<i>Of course, you can't repeat.</i>

512
00:38:55,917 --> 00:38:57,627
<i>This is, like, where the pain comes in,</i>

513
00:38:57,710 --> 00:39:01,840
<i>when I talk about not being good enough,</i>
<i>or being afraid that you're out of ideas.</i>

514
00:39:04,717 --> 00:39:07,507
<i>You measure yourself</i>
<i>against a lucky moment.</i>

515
00:39:09,138 --> 00:39:11,268
<i>And this is, like, really, really painful.</i>

516
00:39:13,142 --> 00:39:15,602
<i>You had this one kind of spark</i>
<i>three years ago,</i>

517
00:39:15,687 --> 00:39:17,687
<i>and then a client asks you to do it again.</i>

518
00:39:19,148 --> 00:39:20,688
<i>And you think, "How can I?</i>

519
00:39:20,775 --> 00:39:21,895
<i>I won the lottery then.</i>

520
00:39:21,985 --> 00:39:25,945
<i>How can you ask me to win the lottery,</i>
<i>under pressure, with a gun to my head?"</i>

521
00:39:26,030 --> 00:39:29,870
<i>And this is something that,</i>
<i>before I consciously thought about it,</i>

522
00:39:29,951 --> 00:39:32,201
<i>I just realized, "Oh, God, I'm miserable."</i>

523
00:39:33,121 --> 00:39:35,421
[chime music continues]

524
00:39:40,461 --> 00:39:41,961
[Christoph]<i> But when I realized</i>

525
00:39:42,046 --> 00:39:46,336
<i>that my fears threatened</i>
<i>to take a toll on my work,</i>

526
00:39:47,010 --> 00:39:49,180
<i>I decided I had to deal with them.</i>

527
00:39:51,764 --> 00:39:54,434
<i>Relax; don't be so hard on yourself.</i>

528
00:39:55,268 --> 00:39:56,938
<i>I actually totally disagree.</i>

529
00:39:58,396 --> 00:40:00,396
<i>You have to practice and become better.</i>

530
00:40:01,274 --> 00:40:05,034
<i>Every athlete, every musician</i>
<i>practices every day.</i>

531
00:40:06,029 --> 00:40:07,659
<i>Why should it be different for artists?</i>

532
00:40:07,739 --> 00:40:09,989
[upbeat music playing]

533
00:40:31,137 --> 00:40:33,597
[Christoph] <i>I sometimes imagine</i>
<i>what would happen</i>

534
00:40:33,681 --> 00:40:37,941
<i>if I had to face</i>
<i>the 2006 version of myself</i>

535
00:40:38,019 --> 00:40:40,899
<i>in some sort of creative bar fight.</i>

536
00:40:41,940 --> 00:40:44,900
<i>Maybe I've lost some of my youthful spark,</i>

537
00:40:45,443 --> 00:40:47,653
<i>but I'm confident I would kick my butt.</i>

538
00:40:54,994 --> 00:40:58,414
<i>The assignment was</i>
<i>to do an augmented reality cover.</i>

539
00:40:59,332 --> 00:41:01,792
In a way,
we have that augmented reality cover,

540
00:41:01,876 --> 00:41:04,296
but this already is
an augmented reality cover,

541
00:41:04,379 --> 00:41:08,009
because you can look at the same scene
from two sides.

542
00:41:08,091 --> 00:41:09,181
I'm inside the subway.

543
00:41:09,258 --> 00:41:13,388
So, essentially what I do with the iPad,
I do with the physical magazine.

544
00:41:13,471 --> 00:41:16,851
As if the magazine is
the door of the subway.

545
00:41:16,933 --> 00:41:20,523
So this is an extension of that,
rather than the other way round.

546
00:41:20,603 --> 00:41:23,063
[muffled female voice]

547
00:41:27,360 --> 00:41:28,990
-Yeah, yeah.
-[muffled female voice]

548
00:41:29,070 --> 00:41:31,820
[muffled female voice continues]

549
00:41:31,906 --> 00:41:34,616
[Christoph] <i>I know how complex it is</i>
<i>to put these different things,</i>

550
00:41:34,701 --> 00:41:36,491
<i>like the 3-D and the animation together,</i>

551
00:41:36,577 --> 00:41:41,617
that I'm surprised
how close it came to what I imagined.

552
00:41:44,043 --> 00:41:46,093
[Lou Reed's "This Magic Moment" playing]

553
00:42:00,309 --> 00:42:01,599
<i>♪ This magic moment ♪</i>

554
00:42:05,148 --> 00:42:08,148
♪ <i>So different and so new ♪</i>

555
00:42:08,526 --> 00:42:10,566
<i>♪ Was like any other ♪</i>

556
00:42:13,948 --> 00:42:15,778
<i>♪ Until I met you ♪</i>

557
00:42:17,702 --> 00:42:19,582
<i>♪ And then it happened ♪</i>

558
00:42:22,582 --> 00:42:26,172
<i>♪ It took me by surprise ♪</i>

559
00:42:26,252 --> 00:42:28,592
<i>♪ I knew that you felt it too ♪</i>

560
00:42:30,298 --> 00:42:32,968
<i>♪ I could see it</i>
<i>By the look in your eyes ♪</i>

561
